{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"70205851-d157-4f09-82ff-bffcefaa8301","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll give you the configuration guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key requirements:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a global/local dotnet tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users invoke (e.g., `dotnet tool run my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be executables.\n\n**Publishing steps:**\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push ./bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. No special packaging beyond `PackAsTool` is needed — dotnet handles the shim automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8bbbca94-7acc-437f-8836-1d15e994ffd7","outputTokens":496,"requestId":"2018:204067:171B704:19CA890:6A052255"},"id":"09b40d50-9b0f-4046-8ceb-c97240f36fbb","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:16:14.991Z","parentId":"6f21b8aa-1a28-4b06-ab7b-33ac9f7a901b"}
